  ('The_Lighthouse', 6, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Table of Contents   –   6  5.11.5   Customers ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ .   286  5.11.6   Dashboards and statistics   ................................ ................................ ................................ .........   286  5.11.7   Use cases   ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ .   286  5.11.8   Program configuration   ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............   287  5.11.9   EPICs / CRs references and Roadmap ................................ ................................ .....................   288  5.11.10   literature   ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................   289  6   Definitions and guidelines   ................................ ................................ ..............................   290  6.1   Key Definitions   ................................ ................................ ................................ ................   290  6.2   RCAI   ................................ ................................ ................................ ...............................   290  6.2.1   Responsible   ................................ ................................ ................................ ..............................   290  6.2.2   Accountable   ................................ ................................ ................................ ..............................   290  6.2.3   Consulted   ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ..   291  6.2.4   Informed   ................................ ................................ ................................ ................................ ....   291  6.2.5   Significance of RACI Roles   ................................ ................................ ................................ .......   291  6.3   Culture Shift of Behavior at service , capability at domain and Use cases at product   ...   291  6.3.1   Encourage teams to:   ................................ ................................ ................................ .................   291  6.4   The Three ‑ Layer Model   —   Refined and Strengthened   ................................ ..................   292  6.4.1  1️⃣   Product Layer → Business Use Cases (Value + Outcomes)   ................................ ..............   292  6.4.2  2️⃣   Platform/Domain Layer → Capabilities (System rules + boundaries)   ................................ ..   292  6.4.3  3️⃣   Service Layer → Behaviours (Executable, atomic, testable)   ................................ ...............   293  6.5   ⭐   How the Three Layers Work Together (Flow Model)   ................................ ...............   293  6.5.1   Product → Platform → Service   ................................ ................................ ................................ .   293  6.5.2   Service → Platform → Product (Feedback Loop)   ................................ ................................ .....   293  6.6   🚀   Recommended Operating Model Across Teams   ................................ .....................   293  6.6.1   Step 1: Use Case Workshops (Product)   ................................ ................................ ...................   293  6.6.2   Step 2: Capability Definition Sessions (Domain)   ................................ ................................ .......   294  6.6.3   Step 3: Behaviour Modelling at Service Level (Engineering)   ................................ ....................   294  6.7   💡   How to Reduce Pain Specifically at the Service Layer   ................................ ............   294  6.7.1   ✅   1. Keep behaviours API - boundary only   ................................ ................................ ...............   294  6.7.2   ✅   2. Behaviours map 1:1 to capabilities   ................................ ................................ ..................   294  6.7.3   ✅   3. Make behaviours the smallest stable unit of functionality   ................................ ................   294  6.7.4   ✅   4. Keep behaviour tests low in number but high in value   ................................ ....................   295  6.7.5   ✅   5. Enforce behaviour versioning   ................................ ................................ ..........................   295  6.8   RACI Matrix [Product dimension]   ................................ ................................ ...................   295  6.9   RACI Matrix [Service dimension]   ................................ ................................ ....................   296'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 7, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Service Dashboards   –   7  The ultimate MACS literature.  Refer   Definitions and guidelines   to understand key concepts, definitions and guidelines to  maintain this literature.  MACS Services  [   Service Dashboards   ] [   Guiding principles   ]  MACS core platform services are composed of Data services and orchestration services. This  section could also cover various peripheral components e.g. libraries, schedulers, UIs.  Each service will have its own ''Service Dashboard'' which gives current snapshot of service  behaviour. Each dashboard with contain various document artifacts and references to cover  characteristics of a given service.  At the end of the page you will find those characteristics and their ownership model and  guidelines to manage relevant literature. That will help you create and maintain various service  artifacts.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 8, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Service Dashboards   –   8  1   Service Dashboards  1.1   Bulk Provisioning Service Dashboard  Bulk Provisioning Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that  manages consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification, which  will transition to the authentication service, and handles consent managemen t, keeping records  of all consents given by consumers.  1.2   Checkout Service Dashboard  Checkout Service is a program sensitive orchestration service within the MACS that manages  appropriate Checkout payload composition.  1.3   Consumer Service Dashboard  Consumer Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that manages  consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification, which will  transition to the authentication service, and handles consent management, keepin g records of  all consents given by consumers.  1.4   DCF Service Dashboard  DCF (Digital Card Facilitator) is a crucial front end UI within Mastercard Click to Pay (C2P) that  provides consumer with access to the selected digital card, interface to review and confirm the  transaction / consumer details and facilitate the payment con firmation  1.5   Directory Orchestrator Service Dashboard  Directory Orchestrator Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that  manages consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification, which  will transition to the authentication service, and handles consent mana gement, keeping records  of all consents given by consumers.  1.6   Middleware Service Dashboard  Middleware is a program sensitive orchestration service within the MACS that manages  appropriate operations to complete the Checkout successfully.  1.7   Payment Instrument Service Dashboard  Payment instrument service is a program agnostic MACS platform service which manages  cards and token (storage provisioning and lifecycle). It also offers transaction credentials and  lookup operations. Payment instrument integrates with the backend systems   like MDES, BNC,  CAAS, ABU, PAM for MACS.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 9, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Service Dashboards   –   9  1.8   Pre - Checkout Service Dashboard  Pre - checkout is a program agnostic orchestration service within the MACS initially built to  support Click - to - Pay (C2P) checkout operations by adhering the EMVCo guidelines.  1.9   Profile Service Dashboard  Checkout Service is a program sensitive orchestration service within the MACS that manages  appropriate Checkout payload composition. ...... <Add overview>'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 10, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   10  2   Guiding principles  2.1   RACI Matrix (Service dimension)  RACI Matrix [Service dimension]  The RACI matrix is a powerful tool used to define roles and responsibilities. It stands for  Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. Here we delve into the definitions  and significance of each role and ownership of various artifacts within Servic e dimension.  RACI Roles Explained  •   Responsible   (R):   The person or people who   do the work   to complete the task.  •   Accountable   (A):   The one person who is   ultimately answerable for the task''s  completion and quality ;   they sign off on the work  •   Consulted   (C):   Subject matter experts   whose input is needed   (two - way  communication) to ensure the task is done correctly.  •   Informed   (I):   Stakeholders or others who need to be   kept in the loop   on progress  and outcomes (one - way communication).  Artifact   AI  Prompt  Place   Ser  vice  PO  Tech.  lead  Dom  ain  Arch  itect  Dev.T  eam  T  P  M  impleme  ntation  Sample  1   Data  Model,  and entity  overview  (for the  Services  having  Data/Entiti  es)  ?  Java code  as an  input  @Amit  Gandontra  Monday  9th March  Separat  e page  Linked  in  dashbo  ard  A   R   R   R   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A and  R only  Consumer service :  Data Model and  Entity overview  2   ER and  Data  definition,  Uniquene  ss and  relationshi  p  (for the  Services  having  Data/Entiti  es)  Natesh  Ganesan  to talk to  DBA team  and get  links per  service  (Anil /  vamsi)  Tuesday  10th  March  Separat  e page  Linked  in  dashbo  ard  C   A/R   C   R   Consumer Service  : ER Diagram  3   Contract/S  wagger   -  for micro -  services  Neeraj  Dase to  provide  prompt.  linked  in  dashbo  ard  A   R   R   R   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A and'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 11, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   11  @  PRashant  for Axon  contract  (9th March  -   Prahshat  to check  with neeraj  for  swagger  timeline)  Generate  Swagger/c  ontracts  for phase  1 services  Natesh  Ganesan  to setup a  call with  tech.lead  to review  and  confirm  the  generated  swaggers  are good   -  move  generated  content to  Service  dashboard  R only,  PRs will  be  reviewed  by R  4   Service  capability  and  configurati  ons (e.g.  program  level  configurab  ility  offered by  service /  service  local  configurati  ons)  Amit  Gandotra  to get  promot   -  we need  to review  output  (finalize  the outout)  Phase 2  Separat  e page  Linked  in  dashbo  ard  A   R   R   R  5   Behavior :  what is  the  behavior  of service  Neeraj  Dase   Dee  pak Gite  link  within  table on  A   C   C   C   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A (Can  Consumer service :  Behaviors : [POST  /consumers]'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 12, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   12  end  point/featu  re of  componen  t  Amit  Gandotra  create  prompt  (ALM, TC,  Code)  TRACK it  actively .  Phase 1 B  12th  March  dashbo  ard  we do this  in  ALM   Dee  pak Gite  Shrikant  Kadam   ?)  <Sample where  matrix has been  used in behavior>  Checkout Service :  Behavior : [POST  /api/transaction/cre  dentials]  6   Functional  Test  Cases  Phase 1.  C  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  C   A   C   R   ALM edit  access  restricted  to Team  Consumer service  Dashboard → end  point and behavior  → Table row  POST /consumers/  searches Table  column Behaviour  → ALM   TF148527  → test folder  TF148427  7   Process  flows /  Sequence  Diagrams  How [per  end point]  Neeraj  Dase   -  Techleads  to review  and  confirm for  phase 1  service   N  atesh  Ganesan  11th  March  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  C   A   C   R   Confluenc  e/Repo  edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  Consumer service  Dashboard → end  point and behavior  → Table row  POST /consumers/  searches Table  column Sequence  diagra   -  search_consumers  _multi_criteria  8   Compone  nt  interaction  diagram  service  level  Amit  Gandotra  @  prashant  to work  together  for promot  phase 1. B  16th  March  Section  on  dashbo  ard  C   R   A   C   Confluenc  e/Repo  edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  Checkout service  dashboard  -   ComponentsInter  action  9   Downstre  am  dependen  cies per  end  point/featu  re  Prashant T  horat  phase 1   -  get the  names  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  C   R   A   C'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 13, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   13  phase 1.B  -   generate  links  10th  March  1  0  KPI per  endpoint  Prashant  thorat  Phase 1  10th  March  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  A   R   C   R   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  refer   Consumer  service Dashboard  → end point and  behavior table  1  1  SLA (TPS  ,Current  (Dynatrac  e link),  Response  time,  Projected  TPS for  EOY  Neeraj   -  Existing  production  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  A   C   C   C   Periodical  ly (Every  Quarter)  fetched  from  ProdOps  and SRE  team  refer Consumer  service Dashboard  → end point and  behavior table  1  2  Operation  al and  Performan  ce  references  Section  on  dashbo  ard  A   C   C   C   PO to  work with  BiZOps  refer Consumer  service Dashboard  -   >   Operational and  Performance  references  1  3  Technical  Roadmap  Separat  e page  Linked  in   dash  board  A   R   C   R   C   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  ONR Tech  Improvements   -  Alberta   -  Confluence  1  4  Technical  Infrastruct  ure  Section  on  dashbo  ard  C   A   C   R   refer Consumer  service Dashboard  1  5  Team and  ALM  Section  on  dashbo  ard  C   C   C   R   A   refer Consumer  service Dashboard  2.2   Guidelines for Content organizations  2.2.1   End Points/Feature Points  At the   service level ,   endpoints   act as key anchors for associating various artifacts. If a service  does not expose endpoints, use   feature points   that represent specific use case or call - to - action'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 14, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   14  e.g., for   UI component   –   ''Add Card'' is a feature point, which has some meaningful operation  with start and end result, dependencies, KPIs, sequence diagrams etc.  2.2.2   Endpoints & Behavior Table  Each service dashboard should include a table under   “Endpoints & Behavior”   to organize:  •   Endpoint/Feature Point   it''s   Behavior   (linked to Confluence page) and   Test Cases  (linked to ALM folder)  •   Behavior Page  Create a dedicated   Behavior   pages under the service dashboard: Set of behavior pages  creates   Repository of Behaviors   for service.  •  o   Naming Convention on confluence:  o   <Service   Name>   :   Behavior   :   [<Endpoint   /   Feature   Point>]  o   Example:   Consumer   Service   :   Behaviors   :   [POST  /consumers]   https://confluence.mastercard.int/x/WnvTgQ  •   ALM Test Folder Structure  o   Team can decide to organize test cases by categories (e.g., Positive, Negative,  common Scenarios).  o   Abstract and encapsulate common logic, validations, and exceptions (OOP  principle).  o   Naming Conventions in ALM:  o   <Service   Name>   :   Functional   Tests   :   [<Endpoint   /   Feature  Point>]  o   Example:   TF148527 :   Consumer   service   :   Functional   Tests   :  [Endpoint:   POST   /consumers/searches]  •   PO to create and manage repository of behaviors for their service offering, similarly  Test case repositories associated with behavior has to be created by technical team.  2.2.3   Behavior Documentation  •   Format:  Use   Gherkin   syntax for behaviors:  o   Business - readable, domain - specific language.  o   Supports BDD (Behavior - Driven Development).  o   Structure:   Given   –   When   –   Then .  •   Benefits:  o   Shared language between Business, QA, and Dev.  o   Human - readable and machine - parsable for automation.  o   Reusable in Agile stories  2.2.4   Other Artifacts  •  o   Data Model, definitions and Entity relationship documents  o   Component diagram, upstream and downstream'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 15, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   15  o   Technical roadmap  o   refer samples  2.3   Content Lifecycle  It is very important to keep the artifacts up to date, Al HL below is the process.  2.3.1   Epic Analysis [pre - decomp phases]  •   Analyze functional/non - functional requirements in context of existing behaviors.  •   Document impact on endpoints, behaviors, test cases, and sequence diagrams in a  separate analysis page   -   focused on changes and new behaviors  •   Changes has been reviewed and confirmed with Domain architect and PM  2.3.2   Post - Decomposition  •   Merge updated behaviors, and sequence diagrams into respective repositories.  •   Mark impacted behaviors as   Proposed   with reference to feature/story in   Change Log  column .  •   Reuse documented behaviors wherever possible in user stories, FTs.  2.3.3   Development  •   Add/Update relevant functional tests in repositories along with implementation of  desired behavior from stories (BAU)  •   Upon acceptance of story , update the behavior repository entry -   remove Mark  Proposed  •   Create a placeholder story to ensure all repositories (Behavior, test cases, sequence  diagrams) are updated after feature completion.  o   The story will be accepted once comments from PO, Tech.lead and Dev.  Manager has been captured   -   confirming that they reviewed artifacts and they  are updated correctly.  Domains and Platform  2.3.4   Actors  •   Actor   -   Consumer  •   Actor   -   Directory Provider  •   Actor   -   Identity Provider  •   Actor   -   Integrator  •   Actor   -   Issuer  •   Actor   -   Merchant'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 16, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   16  2.3.5   API Integration  2.3.6   Architecture  2.3.7   Data principle  •   On - Soil and localization  •   PCI data protection  •   PII data protection  2.3.8   Domains capabilities  •   Checkout Domain Sample  •   Enrollment   -   Domain  •   On boarding  2.3.9   MACS Attribute dictionary  2.3.10   Programs definitions and principles  Programs and Products  2.3.11   Click2Pay  2.3.12   Click - to - Pay Push Provisioning  2.3.13   Guest Checkout tokenization  2.3.14   SCOF   -   VCN   -   Auto form fill  2.3.15   To be re - purposed for C2P  2.4   RACI Matrix (Product dimension)  RACI Matrix [Product dimension]'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 17, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Guiding principles   –   17  The RACI matrix is a powerful tool used to define roles and responsibilities. It stands for  Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. Here we delve into the definitions  and significance of each role and ownership of various artifacts within produc t dimension.  RACI Roles Explained  •   Responsible   (R):   The person or people who   do the work   to complete the task.  •   Accountable   (A):   The one person who is   ultimately answerable for the task''s  completion and quality ;   they sign off on the work  •   Consulted   (C):   Subject matter experts   whose input is needed   (two - way  communication) to ensure the task is done correctly.  •   Informed   (I):   Stakeholders or others who need to be   kept in the loop   on progress  and outcomes (one - way communication).  Artifact   Place   PM   Architect   Sample  1   Product overview   section   A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  2   product Construct   section   A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  3   Actor and Workflow   section   A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  4   Technical workflow   section or link   C   A/R   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  5   Product Use cases, SLA,  dependencies with links to  downstream services  Section with  Table  A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  6   Dashboards and matrix   link within table  on dashboard  A/R   -   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  7   Customers   link within table  on dashboard  A/R   -   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  8   MACS Program configuration   Section on  dashboard  C   A/R   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  9   EPICS CR   link within table  on dashboard  A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  10   Roadmap   A/R   C   ONR Tech  Improvements   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  11   Other references,  Audit report,  Studio references  Dev Zone resources  link within table  on dashboard  A/R   C'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 18, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   18  3   MACS Services  •   Service Dashboards  •   Guiding principles  MACS core platform services are composed of Data services and orchestration services. This  section could also cover various peripheral components e.g. libraries, schedulers, UIs.  Each service will have its own ''Service Dashboard'' which gives current snapshot of service  behaviour. Each dashboard with contain various document artifacts and references to cover  characteristics of a given service.  At the end of the page you will find those characteristics and their ownership model and  guidelines to manage relevant literature. That will help you create and maintain various service  artifacts.  3.1   Service Dashboards  3.1.1   Bulk Provisioning Service Dashboard  Bulk Provisioning Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that  manages consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification, which  will transition to the authentication service, and handles consent managemen t, keeping records  of all consents given by consumers.  3.1.2   Checkout Service Dashboard  Checkout Service is a program sensitive orchestration service within the MACS that manages  appropriate Checkout payload composition.  3.1.3   Consumer Service Dashboard  Consumer Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that manages  consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification, which will  transition to the authentication service, and handles consent management, keepin g records of  all consents given by consumers.  3.1.4   DCF Service Dashboard  DCF (Digital Card Facilitator) is a crucial front end UI within Mastercard Click to Pay (C2P) that  provides consumer with access to the selected digital card, interface to review and confirm the  transaction / consumer details and facilitate the payment con firmation  3.1.5   Directory Orchestrator Service Dashboard  Directory Orchestrator Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that  manages consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification, which  will transition to the authentication service, and handles consent mana gement, keeping records  of all consents given by consumers.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 19, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   19  3.1.6   Middleware Service Dashboard  Middleware is a program sensitive orchestration service within the MACS that manages  appropriate operations to complete the Checkout successfully.  3.1.7   Payment Instrument Service Dashboard  Payment instrument service is a program agnostic MACS platform service which manages  cards and token (storage provisioning and lifecycle). It also offers transaction credentials and  lookup operations. Payment instrument integrates with the backend systems   like MDES, BNC,  CAAS, ABU, PAM for MACS.  3.1.8   Pre - Checkout Service Dashboard  Pre - checkout is a program agnostic orchestration service within the MACS initially built to  support Click - to - Pay (C2P) checkout operations by adhering the EMVCo guidelines.  3.1.9   Profile Service Dashboard  Checkout Service is a program sensitive orchestration service within the MACS that manages  appropriate Checkout payload composition. ...... <Add overview>  3.2   Guiding principles  3.2.1   RACI Matrix (Service dimension)  RACI Matrix [Service dimension]  The RACI matrix is a powerful tool used to define roles and responsibilities. It stands for  Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. Here we delve into the definitions  and significance of each role and ownership of various artifacts within Servic e dimension.  RACI Roles Explained  •   Responsible   (R):   The person or people who   do the work   to complete the task.  •   Accountable   (A):   The one person who is   ultimately answerable for the task''s  completion and quality ;   they sign off on the work  •   Consulted   (C):   Subject matter experts   whose input is needed   (two - way  communication) to ensure the task is done correctly.  •   Informed   (I):   Stakeholders or others who need to be   kept in the loop   on progress  and outcomes (one - way communication).'),
