  ('The_Lighthouse', 21, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   21  to review  and  confirm  the  generated  swaggers  are good   -  move  generated  content to  Service  dashboard  4   Service  capability  and  configurati  ons (e.g.  program  level  configurab  ility  offered by  service /  service  local  configurati  ons)  Amit  Gandotra  to get  promot   -  we need  to review  output  (finalize  the outout)  Phase 2  Separat  e page  Linked  in  dashbo  ard  A   R   R   R  5   Behavior :  what is  the  behavior  of service  end  point/featu  re of  componen  t  Neeraj  Dase   Dee  pak Gite  Amit  Gandotra  create  prompt  (ALM, TC,  Code)  TRACK it  actively .  Phase 1 B  12th  March  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  A   C   C   C   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A (Can  we do this  in  ALM   Dee  pak Gite  Shrikant  Kadam   ?)  Consumer service :  Behaviors : [POST  /consumers]  <Sample where  matrix has been  used in behavior>  Checkout Service :  Behavior : [POST  /api/transaction/cre  dentials]  6   Functional  Test  Cases  Phase 1.  C  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  C   A   C   R   ALM edit  access  restricted  to Team  Consumer service  Dashboard → end  point and behavior  → Table row  POST /consumers/  searches Table  column Behaviour  → ALM   TF148527'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 22, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   22  → test folder  TF148427  7   Process  flows /  Sequence  Diagrams  How [per  end point]  Neeraj  Dase   -  Techleads  to review  and  confirm for  phase 1  service   N  atesh  Ganesan  11th  March  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  C   A   C   R   Confluenc  e/Repo  edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  Consumer service  Dashboard → end  point and behavior  → Table row  POST /consumers/  searches Table  column Sequence  diagra   -  search_consumers  _multi_criteria  8   Compone  nt  interaction  diagram  service  level  Amit  Gandotra  @  prashant  to work  together  for promot  phase 1. B  16th  March  Section  on  dashbo  ard  C   R   A   C   Confluenc  e/Repo  edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  Checkout service  dashboard  -   ComponentsInter  action  9   Downstre  am  dependen  cies per  end  point/featu  re  Prashant T  horat  phase 1   -  get the  names  phase 1.B  -   generate  links  10th  March  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  C   R   A   C  1  0  KPI per  endpoint  Prashant  thorat  Phase 1  10th  March  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  A   R   C   R   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  refer Consumer  service Dashboard  → end point and  behavior table  1  1  SLA (TPS  ,Current  (Dynatrac  e link),  Response  time,  Projected  Neeraj   -  Existing  production  link  within  table on  dashbo  ard  A   C   C   C   Periodical  ly (Every  Quarter)  fetched  from  ProdOps  refer   Consumer  service Dashboard  → end point and  behavior table'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 23, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   23  TPS for  EOY  and SRE  team  1  2  Operation  al and  Performan  ce  references  Section  on  dashbo  ard  A   C   C   C   PO to  work with  BiZOps  refer Consumer  service Dashboard  -   >   Operational and  Performance  references  1  3  Technical  Roadmap  Separat  e page  Linked  in   dash  board  A   R   C   R   C   Confluenc  e edit  access  restricted  to A and  R  ONR Tech  Improvements   -  Alberta   -  Confluence  1  4  Technical  Infrastruct  ure  Section  on  dashbo  ard  C   A   C   R   refer Consumer  service Dashboard  1  5  Team and  ALM  Section  on  dashbo  ard  C   C   C   R   A   refer Consumer  service Dashboard  3.2.2   Guidelines for Content organizations  3.2.2.1   End Points/Feature Points  At the   service level ,   endpoints   act as key anchors for associating various artifacts. If a service  does not expose endpoints, use   feature points   that represent specific use case or call - to - action  e.g., for   UI component   –   ''Add Card'' is a feature point, which has some meaningful operation  with start and end result, dependencies, KPIs, sequence diagrams etc.  3.2.2.2   Endpoints & Behavior Table  Each service dashboard should include a table under   “Endpoints & Behavior”   to organize:  •   Endpoint/Feature Point   it''s   Behavior   (linked to Confluence page) and   Test Cases  (linked to ALM folder)  •   Behavior Page  Create a dedicated   Behavior   pages under the service dashboard: Set of behavior pages  creates   Repository of Behaviors   for service.  •  o   Naming Convention on confluence:  o   <Service   Name>   :   Behavior   :   [<Endpoint   /   Feature   Point>]  o   Example:   Consumer   Service   :   Behaviors   :   [POST  /consumers]   https://confluence.mastercard.int/x/WnvTgQ  •   ALM Test Folder Structure  o   Team can decide to organize test cases by categories (e.g., Positive, Negative,  common Scenarios).'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 24, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   24  o   Abstract and encapsulate common logic, validations, and exceptions (OOP  principle).  o   Naming Conventions in ALM:  o   <Service   Name>   :   Functional   Tests   :   [<Endpoint   /   Feature  Point>]  o   Example:   TF148527 :   Consumer   service   :   Functional   Tests   :  [Endpoint:   POST   /consumers/searches]  •   PO to create and manage repository of behaviors for their service offering, similarly  Test case repositories associated with behavior has to be created by technical team.  3.2.2.3   Behavior Documentation  •   Format:  Use   Gherkin   syntax for behaviors:  o   Business - readable, domain - specific language.  o   Supports BDD (Behavior - Driven Development).  o   Structure:   Given   –   When   –   Then .  •   Benefits:  o   Shared language between Business, QA, and Dev.  o   Human - readable and machine - parsable for automation.  o   Reusable in Agile stories  3.2.2.4   Other Artifacts  •  o   Data Model, definitions and Entity relationship documents  o   Component diagram, upstream and downstream  o   Technical roadmap  o   refer samples  3.2.3   Content Lifecycle  It is very important to keep the artifacts up to date, Al HL below is the process.  3.2.3.1   Epic Analysis [pre - decomp phases]  •   Analyze functional/non - functional requirements in context of existing behaviors.  •   Document impact on endpoints, behaviors, test cases, and sequence diagrams in a  separate analysis page   -   focused on changes and new behaviors  •   Changes has been reviewed and confirmed with Domain architect and PM  3.2.3.2   Post - Decomposition  •   Merge updated behaviors, and sequence diagrams into respective repositories.  •   Mark impacted behaviors as   Proposed   with reference to feature/story in   Change Log  column .  •   Reuse documented behaviors wherever possible in user stories, FTs.  3.2.3.3   Development  •   Add/Update relevant functional tests in repositories along with implementation of  desired behavior from stories (BAU)  •   Upon acceptance of story , update the behavior repository entry -   remove Mark  Proposed'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 25, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   25  •   Create a placeholder story to ensure all repositories (Behavior, test cases, sequence  diagrams) are updated after feature completion.  o   The story will be accepted once comments from PO, Tech.lead and Dev.  Manager has been captured   -   confirming that they reviewed artifacts and they  are updated correctly.  3.3   Bulk Provisioning Service Dashboard  3.3.1   Table of Contents  •   Overview  •   Dependencies  •   Endpoints & behavior  o   Endpoints Overview  o   Directory 2.0 : Directory Consumer Endpoints  o   Directory 2.0 : Program Consumer Endpoints  o   Directory 2.0 : Consumer Manager Endpoints  •   High - Level Design Artifacts  •   Operational and Performance references  •   Technical Roadmap  •   Technical Infrastructure  •   Team and ALM  3.3.2   Overview  •   Description:  Bulk Provisioning Service is a program - agnostic platform service within the MACS that  manages consumer profiles from creation to deletion. It oversees consumer verification,  which will transition to the authentication service, and handles consent managemen t,  keeping records of all consents given by consumers.  •   Purpose & Scope:  o   As an orchestrator service, it delivers significant business value to MACS by  supporting various flows such as B2C (Click To Pay) and B2B (SCOF).  o   It also offers separate directories for each issuer, enhancing trust and  compliance. This allows issuers to securely onboard consumer data and  enables MACS to provide auto - enrolment solutions where issuers remain in  control of their data.  o   Additionally, the MACS supports third - party wallets (e.g. Samsung) by allowing  wallets to provision consumer and wallet information in the directory. This  enables the presentation of wallet credentials during a payment experience and  facilitates seamless l inking or redirection to the Wallet interface when a  consumer selects a wallet for payment.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 26, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  MACS Services   –   26  3.3.3   Dependencies  This table lists and describes all services or systems that provide input or trigger events for this  microservice or rely on data or functionalities from this microservice.  Service Name   Type   Service Dashboard  Pre - Checkout   Upstream  Push Provisioning   Upstream  Profile   Upstream  Account Management Service   Upstream  Checkout   Upstream  Consumer Scheduler   Upstream  CaaS   Downstream  High Level Interactions  3.3.4   Endpoints & behavior  3.3.4.1   Endpoints Overview  Swagger < to update link to swagger>  This table lists all endpoints provided by the microservice along with their HTTP method and a  brief description.'),
