  ('The_Lighthouse', 280, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   280  p  e  M  A  C  S  S  er  vi  c  e  ID  /  Pr  o  gr  a  m  ID  ID   -   GUEST_CHECKOUT_TOKENIZATION  reference to program config  {   "id" :   "GUEST_CHECKOUT_TOKENIZATION" ,   "name" :   "Guest   Checkout   Tokeniz  ation" ,   "description" :   "Guest   Checkout   Tokenization......." ,   "services" :   [   {  "id" :   " http://mastercard.com/src/checkout " ,   "version" :   "1.0.0" ,   "capabilities" :   [  {   "id" :   "checkout" ,   "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "defaultDyna  micDataType" ,   "value" :   "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM_SHORT_FORM"   },  {   "id" :   "supportedDynamicDataType" ,   "value" :   [ "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM  _SHORT_FORM" ]   },   {   "id" :   "supportedUCAFVersion" ,   "value" :   "V0"   },  {   "id" :   "isBillingAddressSupported" ,   "value" :   "false"   },   {   "id" :   "isShippingAddressSu  pported" ,   "value" :   "false"   },   {   "id" :   "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM_SHO  RT_FORM.amount.nill.downgradeOption" ,   "value" :   "DOWNGRADE_TO_V0"   },   {  "id" :   "checkout.supportedTypes" ,   "value" :   [ "ENCRYPTED_CARD" ]   },   {   "id" :   "chec  kout.supportedMbvsTokenTypes" ,   "value" :   [ "CLOUD" ]   },   {   "id" :   "enrollmentType" ,  "value" :   "PAYMENT_ACCOUNT"   }   ]   },   {   "id" :   "client.sr  ci.dpa" ,   "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "request.enableDpaVerification" ,   "value" :  "true"   }   ]   },   {   "id" :   "checkout.digitalaccount.fpan" ,  "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "provision.card.supportedIssuerCountries" ,   "value" :   [   "  356"   ]   },   {   "id" :   "provision.card.allowFpanBasedDigitization" ,   "value" :   "false"   },  {   "id" :   "provision.card.cvcValidationRequested" ,   "value" :   "EXISTING_CARD_SKIP_C  VC"   },   {   "id" :   "provision.card.retentionPeriod" ,   "value" :   "8760"   }   ]  }   ]   },   {   "id" :   " http://mastercard.com/src/push -  notification " ,   "version" :   "1.0.0" ,   "capabilities" :   [   {   "id"   :   "batc  hEnrollmentNotifications" ,   "parameters"   :   [   {   "id"   :   "enableNotifications" ,  "value"   :   true   },   {   "id"   :   "notificationRetryDelaySeconds" , "value"   :   "[900,1800,720  0,72000,144000]"   }   ]   }   ]   }   ]   }  5.7.9   EPICs / CRs references and Roadmap  5.7.9.1   Done  I10348 : MACS   -   On Soil Initiatives (2024)  E63945 : India On Soil |PbA Static Tokens and ICCP VCN   -   Guest Checkout tokenization  enablement [PST]  5.7.9.2   In - Progress  5.7.9.3   Upcoming  E71724: [Alt - ID]   -   Token Broker to support Alt - ID in India  ConnectedModel_MACS_NextSteps_May2025.pptx  5.7.10   literature  MA Dev.Zone   -  https://developer.mastercard.com/product/guest - checkout - tokenization/  Score and analysis   -   POGS Score Drop Analysis for Guest Checkout Tokenization   -   SRC  Checkout Product Strategy   -   Confluence'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 281, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   281  Product and Sales   -  Not available/uploaded  Studio  Guest Checkout Tokenization  Guest Checkout Training.pptx  General  Solutioning  E39367 (MVS)   -   India On Soil   -   M1.0   -   ASAP Phase   -   Alberta   -   Confluence  5.8   Click - to - Pay Push Provisioning  5.8.1   Product construct  5.8.2   Program configuration  5.8.3   Actors and workflow  5.8.4   Customers  5.8.5   Dashboards and statistics  5.8.6   Use cases  5.8.7   EPIC / CR references  5.9   Guest Checkout tokenization  5.9.1   Overview  Guest Checkout Tokenization allows merchants and Payment Service Providers to tokenize  PANs entered by consumers when performing guest checkout. Guest Checkout allows  cardholders to make a purchase without the need to create an account or save their card d etails  with the merchant.  Initially constructed based on RBI   -   India tokenization regulations.  5.9.2   Product construct  5.9.2.1   Guest Checkout Specifics  •   In guest checkout, the card is   not stored   with the integrator  •   Consumer profile   NOT   created  •   Tokenization still happens  •   During checkout, the integrator supplies card details and MACS performs tokenization  as well as requests for transaction credentials (token + cryptogram)'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 282, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   282  o   Transaction credentials will be used to perform payment  •   MACS will reuse the token if same card details are received during checkout  •   Merchant must be onboarded before it can perform Checkout  •   Supports integration via UCS or MCS  5.9.3   Actors, and workflow  Actor Integrator / Actor   -   Merchant  •   Onboards to MACS and integrates with MACS API  •   Onboards Merchants (DPA) to MACS Guest checkout program (via DPA registration)  •   Provides UI/UX for   Programs definitions and principles   to perform Guest checkout  •   Performs MACS Checkout  •   Performs payment process after receiving transaction credentials from MACS  Actor   -   Issuer  •   Has to onboard BIN ranges to guest checkout tokenization program  •   Must support processing of DE48.. elements ??  •   Wil be able to see various indicators while processing payment authorization message  and can use it in authorization decisioning  o   55 M/N  o   CFEN  o   54 ??  Actor   -   Consumer  •   Choose to perform guest checkout on Merchant site not willing to store card information  on merchant site  •   Gets the goods after successful checkout and payment  5.9.4   Technical workflow  5.9.5   Customers  As of now India only  Customer Tracker   -   SRC Checkout Product Strategy   -   Confluence  5.9.6   Dashboards and statistics  5.9.7   Use cases  Use case   service endpoint  Register  DPA  https://api.mastercard.com/srci/onboarding/org/{organization_id}/dpas/batch'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 283, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   283  Update  DPA  https://api.mastercard.com/srci/onboarding/org/{organization_id}/dpas/{srci_dpa_i  d}  Delete  DPA  https://api.mastercard.com/srci/onboarding/org/{organization_id}/dpas/{srci_dpa_i  d}  Check  Status of a  Batch  https://api.mastercard.com/src/onboarding/srci/{src - client -  id}/dpas/batch/status/batch - id  Checkout  with CVC  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  Checkout  without  CVC  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  Checkout  with DSPR  V0  Cryptogra  m  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  Invalid  DPA ID  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  PAN not  Eligible  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  5.9.8   Program configuration  W  ID  327  M  W  A  SRCCLOUDDSRP  T  RI  D  s  c  o  p  e  1 TRID (50146725060)  T  RI  D  L  e  g  al  E  nt  it  y  N  Mastercard Guest Checkout Tokenization'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 284, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   284  a  m  e  C  F  E  N  Mastercard Guest Checkout Tokenization  T  o  k  e  n  s  c  o  p  e  One Unique Token across all Merchants/PSPs  M  A  C  S  S  er  vi  c  e  ID  /  Pr  o  gr  a  m  ID  ID   -   GUEST_CHECKOUT_TOKENIZATION  reference to program config  {   "id" :   "GUEST_CHECKOUT_TOKENIZATION" ,   "name" :   "Guest   Checkout   Tokeniz  ation" ,   "description" :   "Guest   Checkout   Tokenization......." ,   "services" :   [   {  "id" :   " http://mastercard.com/src/checkout " ,   "version" :   "1.0.0" ,   "capabilities" :   [  {   "id" :   "checkout" ,   "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "defaultDyna  micDataType" ,   "value" :   "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM_SHORT_FORM"   },  {   "id" :   "supportedDynamicDataType" ,   "value" :   [ "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM  _SHORT_FORM" ]   },   {   "id" :   "supportedUCAFVersion" ,   "value" :   "V0"   },  {   "id" :   "isBillingAddressSupported" ,   "value" :   "false"   },   {   "id" :   "isShippingAddressSu  pported" ,   "value" :   "false"   },   {   "id" :   "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM_SHO  RT_FORM.amount.nill.downgradeOption" ,   "value" :   "DOWNGRADE_TO_V0"   },   {  "id" :   "checkout.supportedTypes" ,   "value" :   [ "ENCRYPTED_CARD" ]   },   {   "id" :   "chec  kout.supportedMbvsTokenTypes" ,   "value" :   [ "CLOUD" ]   },   {   "id" :   "enrollmentType" ,  "value" :   "PAYMENT_ACCOUNT"   }   ]   },   {   "id" :   "client.sr  ci.dpa" ,   "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "request.enableDpaVerification" ,   "value" :  "true"   }   ]   },   {   "id" :   "checkout.digitalaccount.fpan" ,  "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "provision.card.supportedIssuerCountries" ,   "value" :   [   "  356"   ]   },   {   "id" :   "provision.card.allowFpanBasedDigitization" ,   "value" :   "false"   },  {   "id" :   "provision.card.cvcValidationRequested" ,   "value" :   "EXISTING_CARD_SKIP_C  VC"   },   {   "id" :   "provision.card.retentionPeriod" ,   "value" :   "8760"   }   ]  }   ]   },   {   "id" :   " http://mastercard.com/src/push -  notification " ,   "version" :   "1.0.0" ,   "capabilities" :   [   {   "id"   :   "batc  hEnrollmentNotifications" ,   "parameters"   :   [   {   "id"   :   "enableNotifications" ,  "value"   :   true   },   {   "id"   :   "notificationRetryDelaySeconds" , "value"   :   "[900,1800,720  0,72000,144000]"   }   ]   }   ]   }   ]   }  5.9.9   EPICs / CRs references and Roadmap  5.9.9.1   Done  I10348 : MACS   -   On Soil Initiatives (2024)  E63945 : India On Soil |PbA Static Tokens and ICCP VCN   -   Guest Checkout tokenization  enablement [PST]'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 285, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   285  5.9.9.2   In - Progress  5.9.9.3   Upcoming  E71724: [Alt - ID]   -   Token Broker to support Alt - ID in India  ConnectedModel_MACS_NextSteps_May2025.pptx  5.9.10   literature  MA Dev.Zone   -  https://developer.mastercard.com/product/guest - checkout - tokenization/  Score and analysis   -   POGS Score Drop Analysis for Guest Checkout Tokenization   -   SRC  Checkout Product Strategy   -   Confluence  Product and Sales   -  Not available/uploaded  Studio  Guest Checkout Tokenization  Guest Checkout Training.pptx  General  Solutioning  E39367 (MVS)   -   India On Soil   -   M1.0   -   ASAP Phase   -   Alberta   -   Confluence  5.10   SCOF   -   VCN   -   Auto form fill  5.10.1   Product construct  5.10.2   Program configuration  5.10.3   Actors and workflow  5.10.4   Customers  5.10.5   Dashboards and statistics  5.10.6   Use cases  5.10.7   EPIC / CR references  5.11   To be re - purposed for C2P  5.11.1   Overview  Click - to - Pay pre - checkout is a program - agnostic orchestration service within the MACS. It  interacts with UI and downstream components. Both B2B and B2C Click - to - Pay (C2P)  operations are supported.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 286, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   286  5.11.2   Product construct  5.11.2.1   Pre - checkout Specifics  •   Pre - checkout is used for both OPEN BANKING and SRC.  •   Merchant must be onboarded to perform a valid pre - checkout request.  •   Pre - checkout supports both UCS and MCS requests.   Pre - checkout doesn''t have the  UCS or MCS differentiation while processing the requests.  5.11.3   Actors, and workflow  Actor Integrator / Actor   -   Merchant  •   Onboards to MACS and integrates with MACS API  •   Onboards Merchants (DPA) to MACS Guest checkout program (via DPA registration)  •   Provides UI/UX for   Programs definitions and principles   to perform Guest checkout  •   Performs MACS Checkout  •   Performs payment process after receiving transaction credentials from MACS  Actor   -   Issuer  •   Has to onboard BIN ranges to guest checkout tokenization program  •   Must support processing of DE48.. elements ??  •   Wil be able to see various indicators while processing payment authorization message  and can use it in authorization decisioning  o   55 M/N  o   CFEN  o   54 ??  Actor   -   Consumer  •   Choose to perform guest checkout on Merchant site not willing to store card information  on merchant site  •   Gets the goods after successful checkout and payment  5.11.4   Technical workflow  5.11.5   Customers  As of now India only  Customer Tracker   -   SRC Checkout Product Strategy   -   Confluence  5.11.6   Dashboards and statistics  5.11.7   Use cases  Use case   service endpoint'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 287, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   287  Register  DPA  https://api.mastercard.com/srci/onboarding/org/{organization_id}/dpas/batch  Update  DPA  https://api.mastercard.com/srci/onboarding/org/{organization_id}/dpas/{srci_dpa_i  d}  Delete  DPA  https://api.mastercard.com/srci/onboarding/org/{organization_id}/dpas/{srci_dpa_i  d}  Check  Status of a  Batch  https://api.mastercard.com/src/onboarding/srci/{src - client -  id}/dpas/batch/status/batch - id  Checkout  with CVC  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  Checkout  without  CVC  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  Checkout  with DSPR  V0  Cryptogra  m  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  Invalid  DPA ID  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  PAN not  Eligible  https://api.mastercard.co.in/srci/api/checkout  5.11.8   Program configuration  W  ID  327  M  W  A  SRCCLOUDDSRP  T  RI  D  s  c  o  p  e  1 TRID (50146725060)  T  RI  D  L  e  g  al  E  nt  Mastercard Guest Checkout Tokenization'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 288, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   288  it  y  N  a  m  e  C  F  E  N  Mastercard Guest Checkout Tokenization  T  o  k  e  n  s  c  o  p  e  One Unique Token across all Merchants/PSPs  M  A  C  S  S  er  vi  c  e  ID  /  Pr  o  gr  a  m  ID  ID   -   GUEST_CHECKOUT_TOKENIZATION  reference to program config  {   "id" :   "GUEST_CHECKOUT_TOKENIZATION" ,   "name" :   "Guest   Checkout   Tokeniz  ation" ,   "description" :   "Guest   Checkout   Tokenization......." ,   "services" :   [   {  "id" :   " http://mastercard.com/src/checkout " ,   "version" :   "1.0.0" ,   "capabilities" :   [  {   "id" :   "checkout" ,   "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "defaultDyna  micDataType" ,   "value" :   "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM_SHORT_FORM"   },  {   "id" :   "supportedDynamicDataType" ,   "value" :   [ "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM  _SHORT_FORM" ]   },   {   "id" :   "supportedUCAFVersion" ,   "value" :   "V0"   },  {   "id" :   "isBillingAddressSupported" ,   "value" :   "false"   },   {   "id" :   "isShippingAddressSu  pported" ,   "value" :   "false"   },   {   "id" :   "CARD_APPLICATION_CRYPTOGRAM_SHO  RT_FORM.amount.nill.downgradeOption" ,   "value" :   "DOWNGRADE_TO_V0"   },   {  "id" :   "checkout.supportedTypes" ,   "value" :   [ "ENCRYPTED_CARD" ]   },   {   "id" :   "chec  kout.supportedMbvsTokenTypes" ,   "value" :   [ "CLOUD" ]   },   {   "id" :   "enrollmentType" ,  "value" :   "PAYMENT_ACCOUNT"   }   ]   },   {   "id" :   "client.sr  ci.dpa" ,   "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "request.enableDpaVerification" ,   "value" :  "true"   }   ]   },   {   "id" :   "checkout.digitalaccoun t.fpan" ,  "parameters" :   [   {   "id" :   "provision.card.supportedIssuerCountries" ,   "value" :   [   "  356"   ]   },   {   "id" :   "provision.card.allowFpanBasedDigitization" ,   "value" :   "false"   },  {   "id" :   "provision.card.cvcValidationRequested" ,   "value" :   "EXISTING_CARD_SKIP_C  VC"   },   {   "id" :   "provision.card.retentionPeriod" ,   "value" :   "8760"   }   ]  }   ]   },   {   "id" :   " http://mastercard.com/src/push -  notification " ,   "version" :   "1.0.0" ,   "capabilities" :   [   {   "id"   :   "batc  hEnrollmentNotifications" ,   "parameters"   :   [   {   "id"   :   "enableNotifications" ,  "value"   :   true   },   {   "id"   :   "notificationRetryDelaySeconds" , "value"   :   "[900,1800,720  0,72000,144000]"   }   ]   }   ]   }   ]   }  5.11.9   EPICs / CRs references and Roadmap  5.11.9.1   Done  I10348 : MACS   -   On Soil Initiatives (2024)'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 289, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Programs and Products   –   289  E63945 : India On Soil |PbA Static Tokens and ICCP VCN   -   Guest Checkout tokenization  enablement [PST]  5.11.9.2   In - Progress  5.11.9.3   Upcoming  E71724: [Alt - ID]   -   Token Broker to support Alt - ID in India  ConnectedModel_MACS_NextSteps_May2025.pptx  5.11.10   literature'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 290, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   290  6   Definitions and guidelines  6.1   Key Definitions  •   A   business use case   is realized through   Domain capabilities , which are shaped by  the   behavior   and interactions of various underlying services.  •   Service Behavior   is orchestrated by   Domain Capabilities   to realize a   business use  case  •   Behavior   could be linked with each API/end point, in case of UI   -   behaviors could be  linked with call - to - actions  6.2   RCAI  Understanding RACI: A Framework for Clear Responsibilities  The RACI matrix is a powerful tool used in project management to define roles and  responsibilities. It stands for Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. Here we  delve into the definitions and significance of each role within the RACI framework.  6.2.1   Responsible  The person or people who actually perform the task or activity. This role involves executing and  ensuring all necessary actions are taken to complete the work. Multiple individuals can be  responsible for a task, but accountability remains singular.  6.2.2   Accountable  The individual who is ultimately answerable for the completion of the task. This person ensures  the task is done satisfactorily and oversees the actions of those responsible. There should be  only one accountable person assigned to each task to avoid confus ion.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 291, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   291  6.2.3   Consulted  These individuals or groups are asked for their opinions and feedback. Consulted parties are  typically experts or stakeholders who provide valuable insights and information necessary for  the task. This role involves a two - way communication.  6.2.4   Informed  People who need to be kept up to date on the progress and decisions related to the task. They  do not contribute directly to the completion of the task but are notified about the outcomes. This  role involves one - way communication.  6.2.5   Significance of RACI Roles  •   Clarity: Clearly defines who is responsible and accountable for tasks, which helps  prevent misunderstandings and overlapping responsibilities.  •   Efficiency: Streamlines communication by identifying who needs to be consulted and  informed, ensuring that everyone is kept in the loop appropriately.  •   Accountability: Ensures each task has a single accountable person, fostering ownership  and commitment to project goals.  •   Collaboration: Promotes effective collaboration among team members by specifying  roles and expectations.  In summary, the RACI matrix is an essential framework for delineating roles and responsibilities  in project management. It enhances clarity, efficiency, accountability, and collaboration,  ensuring smooth project execution and successful outcomes.  6.3   Culture Shift of Behavior at service , capability at domain  and Use cases at product  The real shift is cultural.  6.3.1   Encourage teams to:  •   talk in examples  •   challenge vague requirements  •   focus on outcomes, not features  •   use behaviour to drive API design  •   validate behaviours early with downstream consumers  Internal teams should ask:   “What behaviour will break if we change this?” Potential AI  prompt once we have behaviour repo.  This mindset drastically reduces regressions and uncertainty.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 292, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   292  6.4   The Three ‑ Layer Model   —   Refined and Strengthened  6.4.1  1️⃣   Product Layer → Business Use Cases (Value + Outcomes)  This layer defines   why   we build something and   what value   it must deliver.  6.4.1.1   🔹   Characteristics of a good Product ‑ level Use Case:  •   expresses   business intent , not implementation  •   can be validated by users or business stakeholders  •   has clear success metrics  •   comes with example scenarios  6.4.1.2   🔹   Example  Use Case: “Customer recovers payment quickly after failed transaction”  Success = <2 minutes average retry + customer receives clear error reason.  6.4.1.3   🔹   Output artefacts  •   Use case narratives  •   Outcome models (impact mapping / story mapping)  •   High ‑ level example scenarios  These flow into the capability layer.  6.4.2  2️⃣   Platform/Domain Layer → Capabilities (System rules +  boundaries)  This layer defines   how the system behaves at the domain level , not at service boundaries.  Capabilities are stable, high ‑ value, long ‑ lived.  They become the backbone of your behaviour model.  6.4.2.1   🔹   Characteristics of a good Capability:  •   describes a   domain rule   or   domain invariant  •   includes examples that span multiple services  •   independent of specific API designs  •   supports multiple product use cases  6.4.2.2   🔹   Example  Capability: “Platform must ensure idempotent payment retries”  Rules:  •   multiple retry attempts must produce a single payment outcome  •   duplicates must be detected deterministically  •   downstream services must not double ‑ charge  6.4.2.3   🔹   Output artefacts  •   Capability definitions  •   Domain examples (Specification by Example)  •   Platform contract policies (idempotency rules, error models, versioning rules)  These guide service behaviours.'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 293, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   293  6.4.3  3️⃣   Service Layer → Behaviours (Executable, atomic, testable)  This is the most important layer to get right because   this is where pain happens   if  unmanaged.  Service behaviours translate capabilities into   observable system behaviours .  6.4.3.1   🔹   Characteristics of a good Service ‑ level Behaviour:  •   externally observable  •   testable through API / message events  •   aligns with one Capability  •   validates rules at the boundary, not inside  •   stable even when internals change  6.4.3.2   🔹   Example (BDD Style)  Behaviour: “Service returns same payment confirmation ID on repeated retry attempts  within 5 minutes”  This is small, scoped, stable   —   ideal for service ‑ level automation.  6.4.3.3   🔹   Output artefacts  •   Behaviour scenarios (Gherkin or alternative notation)  •   Automated BDD tests at service boundary  •   Living documentation updated through CI  6.5   ⭐   How the Three Layers Work Together (Flow Model)  6.5.1   Product → Platform → Service  1.   Business Use Case   defines value and outcome  ↓  2.   Capabilities   define domain rules to support those outcomes  ↓  3.   Service Behaviours   implement those rules in isolated boundaries  6.5.2   Service → Platform → Product (Feedback Loop)  •   If a behaviour conflicts with domain rules → capability refinement  •   If capability becomes too complex → split or reorganise domain  •   If use case changes → only update capabilities and behaviours downstream  This isolates changes and keeps the system stable.  6.6   🚀   Recommended Operating Model Across Teams  Here’s a model you can roll out org ‑ wide:  6.6.1   Step 1: Use Case Workshops (Product)  •   PM + Architect + Domain Lead'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 294, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   294  •   Define outcomes  •   Define primary/edge scenarios  •   Map them to domain  Deliverable:   Use Case Pack  6.6.2   Step 2: Capability Definition Sessions (Domain)  •   Domain architects + principal engineers  •   Extract long - lived rules  •   Validate examples  •   Identify cross - cutting policies (e.g., errors, idempotency, consistency guarantees)  Deliverable:   Capability Catalogue  6.6.3   Step 3: Behaviour Modelling at Service Level (Engineering)  •   Senior engineers + QA  •   Derive atomic service behaviours  •   Define boundary - level tests  •   Implement and automate behaviours  Deliverable:   Service Behaviour Spec + Automation  6.7   💡   How to Reduce Pain Specifically at the Service Layer  This is where teams typically struggle.  Below are proven rules that make behaviours manageable:  6.7.1   ✅   1. Keep behaviours API - boundary only  Do   not   write behaviours for:  •   DB states  •   internal flows  •   technical edges  •   infrastructure interactions  Only observable external outcomes matter.  6.7.2   ✅   2. Behaviours map 1:1 to capabilities  If you can’t map the behaviour to a capability, the behaviour is probably:  •   too detailed  •   implementation - specific  •   unnecessary  6.7.3   ✅   3. Make behaviours the smallest stable unit of functionality  A behaviour should survive:'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 295, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   295  •   refactors  •   code reorganisation  •   service decomposition  •   schema changes  If it doesn’t → it''s not a behaviour, it’s a unit test.  6.7.4   ✅   4. Keep behaviour tests low in number but high in value  Healthy teams have:  •   5 – 15 behaviours per service   (core)  •   20 – 30 total   (including edge cases)  Beyond this → test suite becomes fragile.  6.7.5   ✅   5. Enforce behaviour versioning  Changing a behaviour   must follow a versioning process , just like APIs.  6.8   RACI Matrix [Product dimension]  The RACI matrix is a powerful tool used to define roles and responsibilities. It stands for  Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. Here we delve into the definitions and  significance of each role and ownership of various artifacts within produc t dimension.  RACI Roles Explained  •   Responsible   (R):   The person or people who   do the work   to complete the task.  •   Accountable   (A):   The one person who is   ultimately answerable for the task''s  completion and quality ;   they sign off on the work  •   Consulted   (C):   Subject matter experts   whose input is needed   (two - way  communication) to ensure the task is done correctly.  •   Informed   (I):   Stakeholders or others who need to be   kept in the loop   on progress and  outcomes (one - way communication).  Artifact   Place   PM   Architect   Sample  1   Product overview   section   A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  2   product Construct   section   A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  3   Actor and Workflow   section   A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  4   Technical workflow   section or link   C   A/R   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence'),
  ('The_Lighthouse', 296, 'Alberta   –   The Lighthouse  Definitions and guidelines   –   296  Artifact   Place   PM   Architect   Sample  5   Product Use cases, SLA,  dependencies with links to  downstream services  Section with  Table  A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  6   Dashboards and matrix   link within table  on dashboard  A/R   -   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  7   Customers   link within table  on dashboard  A/R   -   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  8   MACS Program configuration   Section on  dashboard  C   A/R   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  9   EPICS CR   link within table  on dashboard  A/R   C   Guest Checkout  tokenization   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  10   Roadmap   A/R   C   ONR Tech  Improvements   -   Alberta   -  Confluence  11   Other references,  Audit report,  Studio references  Dev Zone resources  link within table  on dashboard  A/R   C  6.9   RACI Matrix [Service dimension]  The RACI matrix is a powerful tool used to define roles and responsibilities. It stands for  Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed. Here we delve into the definitions and  significance of each role and ownership of various artifacts within Servic e dimension.  RACI Roles Explained  •   Responsible   (R):   The person or people who   do the work   to complete the task.  •   Accountable   (A):   The one person who is   ultimately answerable for the task''s  completion and quality ;   they sign off on the work  •   Consulted   (C):   Subject matter experts   whose input is needed   (two - way  communication) to ensure the task is done correctly.  •   Informed   (I):   Stakeholders or others who need to be   kept in the loop   on progress and  outcomes (one - way communication).  Artifact   AI  Prompt  Place   Ser  vice  PO  Tech.  lead  Dom  ain  Archi  tect  Dev.T  eam  T  P  M  impleme  ntation  Sample  1   Data  Model,  and entity  ov